---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Converter from '../../components/Converter.astro';
import { DPI_VALUES, SENS_VALUES, sensToSlug } from '../../lib/data';
const pair = 'cs2-to-apex';
const fromName = 'CS2';
const toName = 'Apex Legends';
---
<Base title="Convert CS2 Sensitivity to Apex Legends – Free Sensitivity Converter" description="Convert your CS2 sensitivity to Apex Legends instantly. Free converter with eDPI and cm/360 calculations. Keep your aim consistent across both games.">

<section class="hero">
  <h1>Convert CS2 Sensitivity to Apex Legends</h1>
  <p>Match your CS2 aim in Apex Legends with accurate sensitivity conversion.</p>
</section>

<Converter defaultFrom="cs2" defaultTo="apex" />

<div class="grid-section">
  <h2>All CS2 to Apex Legends Conversions</h2>
  {DPI_VALUES.map(dpi => (
    <div>
      <h3>{dpi} DPI</h3>
      <div class="link-grid">
        {SENS_VALUES.map(sens => (
          <a href={`/${pair}/${dpi}-dpi/${sensToSlug(sens)}-sens/`}>{sens.toFixed(2)} sens</a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>

<article class="content">
  <h2>CS2 to Apex Legends Sensitivity Guide</h2>
  <p>CS2 and Apex Legends share a direct one-to-one sensitivity conversion. The multiplier for both games is 1.0, which means your CS2 sensitivity number translates directly to the same number in Apex Legends. If you play CS2 at 1.80 sensitivity, you should use 1.80 in Apex Legends to maintain identical physical mouse feel. This is one of the simplest conversions available and exists because both games share Source engine heritage.</p>
  <p>Apex Legends runs on a heavily modified version of Valve's original Source engine. Respawn Entertainment, the studio behind Apex, was founded by former Infinity Ward developers but built their Titanfall and Apex technology on Source. Because the sensitivity scaling was preserved from the original engine, CS2 and Apex share the same relationship between mouse input and camera rotation.</p>

  <h3>Why the Same Sens Feels Different in Apex</h3>
  <p>Despite the one-to-one conversion, many players report that Apex Legends feels noticeably different from CS2. The primary reason is field of view. Apex uses a wider default FOV of 90 to 110 degrees compared to CS2's fixed FOV. A wider field of view makes targets appear smaller and move across more screen space, creating the perception that your sensitivity is slower even when the rotational speed is mathematically identical.</p>
  <p>Movement speed is another factor. Apex Legends features sliding, wall climbing, ziplines, and legend abilities that create rapid position changes. Tracking a moving target in Apex requires sustained mouse movement patterns that CS2 rarely demands. This does not mean your sensitivity is wrong, it means the gameplay demands different applications of the same physical aim.</p>

  <h2>Optimizing Apex Settings After Converting</h2>
  <p>After applying your CS2 sensitivity in Apex Legends, take time to configure the additional sensitivity options that Apex provides. Apex has separate sensitivity multipliers for each zoom level when using scoped weapons. These per-optic settings let you fine-tune ADS sensitivity independently of your base hipfire sensitivity. Most competitive Apex players use an ADS multiplier between 0.8 and 1.0 to maintain close-to-hipfire feel while aiming down sights.</p>
  <p>The firing range is the best place to verify your converted sensitivity. Practice tracking the moving targets at various distances and flicking between the stationary dummies. Your hipfire tracking should feel identical to tracking in CS2 deathmatch if the conversion is applied correctly.</p>

  <h3>Sensitivity Needs in Battle Royale</h3>
  <p>Battle royale gameplay demands versatility that round-based tactical shooters do not. In a single Apex match you might engage in a point-blank shotgun fight, a medium-range AR duel, and a long-distance sniper exchange. Your base sensitivity needs to handle all of these scenarios comfortably. Players coming from CS2 are generally well-served by their existing sensitivity for the close and medium range fights that make up most of Apex's combat.</p>
  <p>Some CS2 players feel they need slightly higher sensitivity in Apex to handle the game's faster pace. If you find this is the case, increase by small amounts, no more than 0.1 to 0.2 at a time. The per-optic ADS multipliers can address ranged precision without changing your base sensitivity, letting you keep muscle memory intact for hipfire and close-quarters fights.</p>

  <h2>Common CS2 to Apex Sensitivity Settings</h2>
  <p>Since the conversion is one-to-one, the numbers are straightforward. At 800 DPI a CS2 sensitivity of 1.00 gives you an eDPI of 800 in both games. A sensitivity of 1.50 at 800 DPI gives an eDPI of 1200. The full range of conversions for every sensitivity and DPI combination is available in the grid above, with each page providing detailed eDPI and cm/360 calculations plus contextual analysis of where that setting falls among competitive players.</p>
</article>

</Base>
